about how I got interested in it.

00:03:08.450 --> 00:03:10.760
As Tomoko said, my
background is in other things,

00:03:10.760 --> 00:03:12.440
particularly microbial genetics.

00:03:12.440 --> 00:03:14.610
But I've always been
interested in evolution.

00:03:14.610 --> 00:03:19.240
And I think it's safe to say that
for most of the 20th century,

00:03:19.240 --> 00:03:24.830
evolutionary biology had a
very self-consistent reasonable

00:03:24.830 --> 00:03:26.180
logical theory.

00:03:26.180 --> 00:03:28.990
But there is a real
lack of specificity

00:03:28.990 --> 00:03:33.620
to how much one could say about
specific evolutionary changes,

00:03:33.620 --> 00:03:35.860
for which there was evidence.

00:03:35.860 --> 00:03:39.840
But we could not tie specific
genes and genetic factors

00:03:39.840 --> 00:03:42.320
to particular evolutionary changes.

00:03:42.320 --> 00:03:44.010
So, in a way it was a kind of.

00:03:44.010 --> 00:03:47.690
It was a good theory, but it
lacked a certain kind of rigor.

00:03:47.690 --> 00:03:53.960
But beginning in the 1970s and
acquiring strength in the 1980s,

00:03:53.960 --> 00:03:57.480
it began to be possible to
isolate genes, specifically.

00:03:57.480 --> 00:03:59.540
And make very specific hypotheses

00:03:59.540 --> 00:04:03.370
about what particular genes
were doing in evolution.

00:04:03.370 --> 00:04:07.380
Not the least in how
particular genes were responsible

00:04:07.380 --> 00:04:10.200
for particular traits
in different organisms.

00:04:10.200 --> 00:04:13.750
And for some of the interest
in evolution or biology,

00:04:13.750 --> 00:04:15.570
this is the prospect
of scientific heaven.

00:04:15.570 --> 00:04:19.640
To be able to really
have good concrete ideas

00:04:19.640 --> 00:04:21.420
about what genes might be involved

00:04:21.420 --> 00:04:24.910
in evolutionary changes
of particular kinds.

00:04:24.910 --> 00:04:28.840
So, I wasn't involved as a
laboratory scientist, in this work.

00:04:28.840 --> 00:04:31.650
But I was very interested in
it, and I wrote commentaries.

00:04:31.650 --> 00:04:34.360
And I finally, wrote a book
that summed up the state

00:04:34.360 --> 00:04:38.770
of the field, which
came out in 2002.

00:04:38.770 --> 00:04:43.090
And shortly after the book became
published, I found myself thinking,

00:04:43.090 --> 00:04:45.840
''Well, how might this
kind of thinking apply

00:04:45.840 --> 00:04:50.810
to human evolution?'' We are a
distinctive looking animal species.

00:04:50.810 --> 00:04:52.110
We are animals.

00:04:52.110 --> 00:04:53.420
Of course, we are a lot more.

00:04:53.420 --> 00:04:56.050
Our species is unique
in what it does

00:04:56.050 --> 00:04:58.650
in the world, and what it has done.

00:04:58.650 --> 00:05:04.230
But surely, there would be a
scope, I felt, for this new branch

00:05:04.230 --> 00:05:07.700
of evolutionary biology, called
evolutionary developmental biology.

00:05:07.700 --> 00:05:12.440
To say something interesting
about humans, human evolution.

00:05:12.440 --> 00:05:15.980
And surely, after having
this thought, I felt, ''Ah,

00:05:15.980 --> 00:05:19.880
the human face might be a
particularly interesting aspect

00:05:19.880 --> 00:05:23.370
of human characteristics,
of human biology,

00:05:23.370 --> 00:05:26.790
to focus on.'' It was more
just a hunch and a feeling.

00:05:26.790 --> 00:05:30.370
Because at the time, actually
there was very little one could say

00:05:30.370 --> 00:05:34.590
about the genes that are involved
in constructing the human face.

00:05:34.590 --> 00:05:39.690
And that might be involved in the
evolutionary series that gave rise

00:05:39.690 --> 00:05:42.810
to our species, and out
particular kind of face.

00:05:42.810 --> 00:05:46.280
For various reasons, I couldn't
start on the book, right away.

00:05:46.280 --> 00:05:49.380
Having to do with work
and other projects.

00:05:49.380 --> 00:05:53.900
And I didn't really start on
it in a serious way until 2011.

00:05:53.900 --> 00:05:56.620
And it was a good thing that
I waited, because in a sense,

00:05:56.620 --> 00:05:59.010
there was very little known
when I first had the idea.

00:05:59.010 --> 00:06:01.280
By the time I got started
on the book,

00:06:01.280 --> 00:06:02.980
there was a great deal
more information.

00:06:02.980 --> 00:06:06.500
So, in effect, the field had caught
up with my ambitions to write

00:06:06.500 --> 00:06:08.820
about it, which was nice.

00:06:08.820 --> 00:06:10.970
Okay. So, let us.

00:06:10.970 --> 00:06:15.410
I'll just add one more thing.

00:06:15.410 --> 00:06:19.970 position:56%
That is that in the sense, as I
worked on the book I found the focus

00:06:19.970 --> 00:06:25.140
of my interest changing, somewhat,
from that of how the genes

00:06:25.140 --> 00:06:27.620
that are involved in
making the human face.

00:06:27.620 --> 00:06:30.510
How they'd evolved and how
their expression characteristics

00:06:30.510 --> 00:06:31.810
had changed.

00:06:31.810 --> 00:06:34.580
More to the why of this.

00:06:34.580 --> 00:06:37.520
What was it in our
evolutionary history,

00:06:37.520 --> 00:06:39.900
the evolution of our species,

00:06:39.900 --> 00:06:43.350
that really has made
us the species we are?

00:06:43.350 --> 00:06:47.110
So, while my official title for
this talk is ''Making Faces,

00:06:47.110 --> 00:06:49.390
the Evolutionary Origins
of the Human Face'',

00:06:49.390 --> 00:06:51.550
The alternative title
gives more of a hint

00:06:51.550 --> 00:06:53.970
as to what I'm going to focus on.

00:06:53.970 --> 00:06:58.130
How our evolving face
helped make us human.

00:06:58.130 --> 00:07:02.190
Okay. So, let us begin
with a basic question.

00:07:02.190 --> 00:07:04.240
What precisely do we
mean by the face?

00:07:04.240 --> 00:07:06.030
Now, we all recognize faces.

00:07:06.030 --> 00:07:09.000
And even in this sort
of caricature of form,

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:10.590
that is Clerdia [phonetic] face.

00:07:10.590 --> 00:07:12.120
But how do we define the face?

00:07:12.120 --> 00:07:15.830
It's always good to start with a
clear definition of one's subject.

00:07:15.830 --> 00:07:21.180 position:56%
And briefly, the face is the forward
directed part of the animal's head

00:07:21.180 --> 00:07:23.610
with a mouth and three
kinds of sense organs

00:07:23.610 --> 00:07:25.720
for vision, smell, and taste.

00:07:25.720 --> 00:07:31.860
Forward directed means the
face is set in the direction

00:07:31.860 --> 00:07:35.820
of movement of the animal.

00:07:35.820 --> 00:07:40.830
So, our faces do, indeed, look
forward toward the environment

00:07:40.830 --> 00:07:42.300
that the animal is entering.

00:07:42.300 --> 00:07:48.400
And what I have here, is pictures
represented of vertebrates.

00:07:48.400 --> 00:07:51.830
So, we are in the group of
animals termed the vertebrates,

00:07:51.830 --> 00:07:56.270
which are a subdivision of a
major group called the Chordata.

00:07:56.270 --> 00:07:59.830
We needn't go into
those details very much.

00:07:59.830 --> 00:08:02.210
But the vertebrates, all
the animals with backbones,

00:08:02.210 --> 00:08:04.710
consist of about 50,000 species.

00:08:04.710 --> 00:08:06.910
Which is roughly a
half to one percent

00:08:06.910 --> 00:08:11.150
of all the estimated existing
animal species in the world.

00:08:11.150 --> 00:08:13.830
Still, 50,000 is a big number.

00:08:13.830 --> 00:08:16.740
And all vertebrates have
faces, as you can see, here.

00:08:16.740 --> 00:08:21.220
We cannot see the sensor
organs very directly,

00:08:21.220 --> 00:08:23.060
in this, but of course, you can.

00:08:23.060 --> 00:08:26.050
Well, except for the eyes.

00:08:26.050 --> 00:08:32.550
So, what we have here, is a fish,
an amphibian, a reptile, bird.

00:08:32.550 --> 00:08:36.720
And two of my favorite
mammalian species, wolves and us.

00:08:36.720 --> 00:08:43.700 position:56%
And they all have eyes and some sort
of visible nostrils for olfaction.

00:08:43.700 --> 00:08:48.700
We can't see the organs of taste,
because they're within the mouth.

00:08:48.700 --> 00:08:51.280
So, another way of putting this,

00:08:51.280 --> 00:08:56.070
is to say that the face is the
sensory headquarters of the animal.

00:08:56.070 --> 00:08:59.650
Okay. It's a really concentrated
area of the animal's body,

00:08:59.650 --> 00:09:03.650
that had three of the main
kinds of sensor organs.

00:09:03.650 --> 00:09:08.410
With, of course, the organs of
hearing, just behind the face.

00:09:08.410 --> 00:09:13.000
And they are in close
association with the mouth.

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:16.080
Now, why is the face
constructed this way?

00:09:16.080 --> 00:09:20.050 position:56%
Well, we get a clue from considering
the evidence that we have

00:09:20.050 --> 00:09:23.410
on the earliest vertebrates,
which were tiny fish.

00:09:23.410 --> 00:09:26.240
And they did, indeed, have,
from everything we know.

00:09:26.240 --> 00:09:27.540
Of course, we don't know directly

00:09:27.540 --> 00:09:30.760
about their organs of
taste and olfaction.

00:09:30.760 --> 00:09:34.180
But they had two eyes in
association with the mouth.

00:09:34.180 --> 00:09:40.570
And this must have been, for them,
a tremendous aid to being able

00:09:40.570 --> 00:09:43.850
to find food and to ingest it.

00:09:43.850 --> 00:09:48.160
To have the eyes and the organs
of olfaction near the mouth,

00:09:48.160 --> 00:09:51.670
helps the animal, of
course, to find food.

00:09:51.670 --> 00:09:56.240
If you imagine the eyes and the
organs of olfaction back here,

00:09:56.240 --> 00:09:58.660
you can see that they wouldn't
be nearly as useful to the animal

00:09:58.660 --> 00:10:03.250 position:56%
for finding food, as if they were
in close association with the mouth.

00:10:03.250 --> 00:10:08.800
So, having defined the face,
let's come to the question

00:10:08.800 --> 00:10:11.810
of what makes the human face
particularly worth talking about?

00:10:11.810 --> 00:10:14.500
Is it just because it's
the face of our species?

00:10:14.500 --> 00:10:16.600
Quite naturally, we are
interested in things

00:10:16.600 --> 00:10:18.110
that relate directly to us.

00:10:18.110 --> 00:10:21.680
Just as most of us are more
interested in our family

00:10:21.680 --> 00:10:23.570
and friends, than people
down the block,

00:10:23.570 --> 00:10:25.250
whom we might see most every day.

00:10:25.250 --> 00:10:26.930
But whom we don't know
anything about.

00:10:26.930 --> 00:10:29.640
So, is the face primarily
interesting just

00:10:29.640 --> 00:10:31.120
because it is our face?

00:10:31.120 --> 00:10:35.530
Or is it, in fact, something, a
rather special and unusual face?

00:10:35.530 --> 00:10:39.090
And I'm going to argue,
briefly, that it is, indeed,

00:10:39.090 --> 00:10:41.650 position:56%
a very special and interesting face.

00:10:41.650 --> 00:10:43.590
So, to answer this question.

00:10:43.590 --> 00:10:45.280
If you're going to argue
there's something special,

00:10:45.280 --> 00:10:48.380
it's got to be special in
comparison to something else.

00:10:48.380 --> 00:10:52.010
And so, we need to compare it,
in this case, with other faces.

00:10:52.010 --> 00:10:53.900 position:56%
And let's just focus on the mammals,

00:10:53.900 --> 00:10:58.820
which is our major subgroup
within the vertebrates.

00:10:58.820 --> 00:11:00.660
So, first of all, let me just admit

00:11:00.660 --> 00:11:03.180
that there are some very
interesting, unusual,

00:11:03.180 --> 00:11:05.920
indeed special, faces
amongst mammals.

00:11:05.920 --> 00:11:08.430
And we have an assortment
of these, here.

00:11:08.430 --> 00:11:10.740
No need to go into details.

00:11:10.740 --> 00:11:13.110
You can see, immediately,
that they're not like you cat

00:11:13.110 --> 00:11:15.900
or your dog, which are
more typical mammals.

00:11:15.900 --> 00:11:18.700
But the great majority of
mammals actually do have a kind

00:11:18.700 --> 00:11:20.560
of typical generic face.

00:11:20.560 --> 00:11:24.710
There are 18 divisions within
the mammals, called orders.

00:11:24.710 --> 00:11:27.020
Okay. It's a taxonomic term.

00:11:27.020 --> 00:11:30.460 position:56%
And I've shown here, typical members

00:11:30.460 --> 00:11:33.790
of eight different
orders of mammals.

00:11:33.790 --> 00:11:37.850 position:56%
And if I pick the examples from
most of the other orders of mammals,

00:11:37.850 --> 00:11:40.960
it would be a similar picture.

00:11:40.960 --> 00:11:45.880
The features that the typical
mammal has, are a muscle.

00:11:45.880 --> 00:11:49.530
Okay. Rather well-spaced eyes.

00:11:49.530 --> 00:11:51.380
Fur on the face.

00:11:51.380 --> 00:11:54.620
You can see that in all of these.

00:11:54.620 --> 00:11:55.920
And no real forehead.

00:11:55.920 --> 00:11:59.570
The head sort of slopes back,
gently, from just above the eyes.

00:11:59.570 --> 00:12:03.460
And those are the features
that make for a commonality

00:12:03.460 --> 00:12:05.920
in the faces of most mammals.

00:12:05.920 --> 00:12:08.930
And once one has realized
that, one sees that, in fact,

00:12:08.930 --> 00:12:11.800
even amongst some of the
oddballs that I showed earlier.

00:12:11.800 --> 00:12:16.250
Some of them have at least one
or two of those common features.

00:12:16.250 --> 00:12:18.220
And without going into
the details, though,

00:12:18.220 --> 00:12:21.250
just you know, make that point.

00:12:21.250 --> 00:12:23.610
But having accepted that fact

00:12:23.610 --> 00:12:25.860
that there is this set
of common features.

00:12:25.860 --> 00:12:29.810
We then come to the
rather surprising fact,

00:12:29.810 --> 00:12:32.570
that one of the most
unusual mammalian faces,

00:12:32.570 --> 00:12:35.580
is that of homo sapiens.

00:12:35.580 --> 00:12:37.240
That's ourselves.

00:12:37.240 --> 00:12:41.140 position:56%
Okay. And since most of us in this
room tend to think of the human face

00:12:41.140 --> 00:12:44.720
as the prototypical,
hence, normal face.

00:12:44.720 --> 00:12:47.650
It may be a surprise to think
that we actually have a very odd

00:12:47.650 --> 00:12:49.480
and different animal face.

00:12:49.480 --> 00:12:53.940
So, instead of just your
taking my word for this claim,

00:12:53.940 --> 00:12:57.150
that our face is particularly
unusual.

00:12:57.150 --> 00:13:00.960
I decided to quote an authority,
here, a man named Donald Enlow.

00:13:00.960 --> 00:13:03.370
I'm not sure if he's still alive.

00:13:03.370 --> 00:13:08.440
But he is or was one
of the great experts

00:13:08.440 --> 00:13:11.220
on the craniofacial skeleton.

00:13:11.220 --> 00:13:14.480
In other words, the skull
and the bones of the face.

00:13:14.480 --> 00:13:16.440
And here, I'll just read out,
even though you can read it.

00:13:16.440 --> 00:13:17.740
I'll read it out.

00:13:17.740 --> 00:13:19.480
''The human face is different.

00:13:19.480 --> 00:13:23.110
Bu ordinary mammalian standards,
our facial features are unusual,

00:13:23.110 --> 00:13:25.880
specialized, and perhaps
even grotesque.

00:13:25.880 --> 00:13:28.110
The long functional
muscle that marks the face

00:13:28.110 --> 00:13:31.400
of most other mammalian forms,
is all but lacking in man.

00:13:31.400 --> 00:13:33.030
The associated snout is reduced

00:13:33.030 --> 00:13:36.900
to a curious overhanging
vestige.'' Known as our nose.

00:13:36.900 --> 00:13:42.080
''The face is wide, flat, and
vertically disposed.'' Okay.

00:13:42.080 --> 00:13:45.520
We have these flat, and indeed,
vertically disposed faces.

00:13:45.520 --> 00:13:49.910 position:56%
''instead of graceful facial contour
sloping back to the skull roof,

00:13:49.910 --> 00:13:54.990
the human face possesses a unique
bulbous, upright forehead in front

00:13:54.990 --> 00:13:57.330
of an enormous braincase.

00:13:57.330 --> 00:14:01.050
The flattened face is diminutive in
character relative to the remainder

00:14:01.050 --> 00:14:03.700
of the enlarged head.''
So, our faces are small,

00:14:03.700 --> 00:14:06.410
relative to that of
most other mammals.

00:14:06.410 --> 00:14:08.580
''The eyes are close together
and they face straight forward.

00:14:08.580 --> 00:14:11.840
The human dental arches are
disproportionately small relative

00:14:11.840 --> 00:14:18.590
to the size of the whole body.'' In
other words, we have smaller teeth.

00:14:18.590 --> 00:14:23.190
Okay. Indeed, the physical
features of our face are unusual.

00:14:23.190 --> 00:14:26.600
And for an evolutionary
biologist, that's interesting.

00:14:26.600 --> 00:14:30.530
But what makes the human face
truly unusual is not its structure,

00:14:30.530 --> 00:14:31.860
but its behavior.

00:14:31.860 --> 00:14:33.220
And specifically, its capacity

00:14:33.220 --> 00:14:36.660
for different expressions,
as illustrated here.

