00:33:30.150 --> 00:33:33.870
There are debates about what the
resemblances and differences are.

00:33:33.870 --> 00:33:37.820
But we can take a modern chimp
as a crude representative

00:33:37.820 --> 00:33:42.560
of the earliest member of the
branch that led to humans.

00:33:42.560 --> 00:33:44.140
And we see some of
the changes, here.

00:33:44.140 --> 00:33:46.060
I'm not going to go
into them in detail.

00:33:46.060 --> 00:33:48.360
But I think you can see
that this modern human face,

00:33:48.360 --> 00:33:51.220
which is a bushman
from South Africa.

00:33:51.220 --> 00:33:55.160
Really is a smaller face
than these longer faces

00:33:55.160 --> 00:34:01.150
of these more apelike
humanlike creatures.

00:34:01.150 --> 00:34:04.450
It's a smaller face,
it's flat, it's vertical.

00:34:04.450 --> 00:34:07.430
There isn't really
any sign of a muzzle.

00:34:07.430 --> 00:34:10.670
Okay. There's a broad forehead.

00:34:10.670 --> 00:34:16.190
Okay. So, what were the major
changes in the second stage?

00:34:16.190 --> 00:34:19.630
The complete loss of the muzzle in.

00:34:19.630 --> 00:34:22.280
You know, the complete
loss of the muzzle.

00:34:22.280 --> 00:34:24.290
Flattening and verticalization
of the face.

00:34:24.290 --> 00:34:26.030
So, we really have vertical faces,

00:34:26.030 --> 00:34:28.910
unlike faces that have
projecting snout.

00:34:28.910 --> 00:34:32.100
The gain of the forehead and
behind that, our big brain.

00:34:32.100 --> 00:34:38.000
And I'm now going to concentrate on
this, because it's quite important.

00:34:38.000 --> 00:34:43.810
One, it really has changed
our look as an animal.

00:34:43.810 --> 00:34:50.060
And secondly, this is connected
to the growth of our big brain,

00:34:50.060 --> 00:34:56.970
which has certainly been a major
contributor to the fact that we are

00:34:56.970 --> 00:34:59.420
such a facially expressive animal.

00:34:59.420 --> 00:35:03.020
And that those expressions
have played a huge part

00:35:03.020 --> 00:35:08.140
in our evolution a
what we are, today.

00:35:08.140 --> 00:35:16.220
So, one of the driving forces, or
one of the trains in our evolution,

00:35:16.220 --> 00:35:21.570
has been the increasing brain size,
shown here fairly diagrammatically.

00:35:21.570 --> 00:35:25.200
And these are inferred
brains, because of course,

00:35:25.200 --> 00:35:27.310
the brains themselves
haven't been preserved.

00:35:27.310 --> 00:35:29.920
What we have is the skulls.

00:35:29.920 --> 00:35:32.660
And from the skulls you
can reconstruct some

00:35:32.660 --> 00:35:34.940
of the surface features
of the brain.

00:35:34.940 --> 00:35:38.340
But these are, as I say,
somewhat imaginative depictions

00:35:38.340 --> 00:35:44.740
of the changes in brain size
that have occurred in the course

00:35:44.740 --> 00:35:50.150
of our developing from
the first hominins.

00:35:50.150 --> 00:35:54.890
The first humanlike animals,
over roughly, 6 million years.

00:35:56.350 --> 00:35:58.660
So, what drove the increase
in human brain size?

00:35:58.660 --> 00:36:00.280
This is really an important

00:36:00.280 --> 00:36:03.210
and interesting question
that's fundamental

00:36:03.210 --> 00:36:06.060
to understanding human evolution.

00:36:06.060 --> 00:36:11.540
The first key point is that
something must have driven this,

00:36:11.540 --> 00:36:13.410
because brains are expensive.

00:36:13.410 --> 00:36:15.650 position:56%
Expensive in terms of energy, hence,

00:36:15.650 --> 00:36:18.280
in the amount of nutrients
that we have to take in.

00:36:18.280 --> 00:36:20.940
The comprise only about
two percent of body weight,

00:36:20.940 --> 00:36:23.450
which doesn't sound
like a large percentage.

00:36:23.450 --> 00:36:25.830
But it's a relatively
large amount for an animal.

00:36:25.830 --> 00:36:29.210
But they require 20% of the
energy needed by the body.

00:36:29.210 --> 00:36:32.120
Okay. So, brains are
energetically expensive.

00:36:32.120 --> 00:36:36.210
And that makes demands on the
animal for adequate nutrition.

00:36:36.210 --> 00:36:40.280
Okay. So, there are three
general explanations.

00:36:40.280 --> 00:36:42.260
I'm going to run through
them fairly quickly

00:36:42.260 --> 00:36:44.880 position:56%
and not do any of them real justice.

00:36:44.880 --> 00:36:46.690
But just to sketch them out.

00:36:46.690 --> 00:36:49.290
There's the better
nutrition hypothesis.

00:36:49.290 --> 00:36:53.400
The need for greater intelligence
for foraging and hunting.

00:36:53.400 --> 00:36:58.440
And finally, the third hypothesis
is that it the growing array

00:36:58.440 --> 00:37:01.230
of social interactions,
something known

00:37:01.230 --> 00:37:05.930 position:56%
as the social brain hypothesis, that
drove the increase in brain size.

00:37:05.930 --> 00:37:08.270 position:56%
So, the better nutrition hypothesis.

00:37:08.270 --> 00:37:10.310
There are several variants of this.

00:37:10.310 --> 00:37:13.920
I think one of the favorite ones
comes from Richard Wrangham,

00:37:13.920 --> 00:37:18.160
who is a professor at Harvard, and
a friend and colleague of mine.

00:37:18.160 --> 00:37:23.640 position:56%
And essentially, is that when humans
learned how to cook they were able

00:37:23.640 --> 00:37:27.000
to increase the efficiency

00:37:27.000 --> 00:37:29.390
with which they extracted
calories from food.

00:37:29.390 --> 00:37:31.770
And there's a lot of
evidence for this.

00:37:31.770 --> 00:37:38.020
But it's not clear to me that
simply having more easier access

00:37:38.020 --> 00:37:41.430
to more energy would have driven
the increase in brain size.

00:37:41.430 --> 00:37:45.070
I think the more plausible
explanation is

00:37:45.070 --> 00:37:52.290
that there were pressures for
increased complexity of behaviors

00:37:52.290 --> 00:37:54.350 position:56%
and various brain related functions.

00:37:54.350 --> 00:37:56.640
Which required better nutrition.

00:37:56.640 --> 00:37:59.450
But the better nutrition itself,

00:37:59.450 --> 00:38:02.120
which he has emphasized
comes from cooking.

00:38:02.120 --> 00:38:06.280
And cooking [inaudible] releases
more readily available energy.

00:38:06.280 --> 00:38:13.110 position:56%
I think that simply the availability
of more energy by cooking food,

00:38:13.110 --> 00:38:17.580
probably does not explain
the increase in brain size.

00:38:17.580 --> 00:38:21.330
And there are other
variance of this hypothesis,

00:38:21.330 --> 00:38:26.350
but they all emphasize
increased energy availability

00:38:26.350 --> 00:38:28.650
from foods as the driving force.

00:38:28.650 --> 00:38:32.530
So, I think that this is unlikely.

00:38:32.530 --> 00:38:35.030
I would say it's an
insufficient reason

00:38:35.030 --> 00:38:37.100
to explain the increase
in brain size.

00:38:37.100 --> 00:38:39.700
What about the need for
greater intelligence

00:38:39.700 --> 00:38:41.160
for foraging and hunting?

00:38:41.160 --> 00:38:46.500
There's no question that foraging
and hunting as humans do it,

00:38:46.500 --> 00:38:48.310
it often more sophisticated,

00:38:48.310 --> 00:38:51.400
even often a much more
sophisticated way of getting food.

00:38:51.400 --> 00:38:55.210
Than the way most of our
brother animals get their food.

00:38:55.210 --> 00:39:00.110
Including our nearest
relatives amongst the primates.

00:39:00.110 --> 00:39:03.270
So, I think that for
various reasons,

00:39:03.270 --> 00:39:05.790
which I'm not going to detail here.

00:39:05.790 --> 00:39:10.520
I think that this is
unconvincing as the prime driver

00:39:10.520 --> 00:39:12.940
of what has made our brains bigger.

00:39:12.940 --> 00:39:18.320
This is unconvincing as the major
selective force for larger brains.

00:39:18.320 --> 00:39:19.620
What about the third one?

00:39:19.620 --> 00:39:20.920
The growing array of
social interactions?

00:39:20.920 --> 00:39:23.400
The social brain hypothesis.

00:39:23.400 --> 00:39:25.560
There isn't time to
go into all of this,

00:39:25.560 --> 00:39:28.150
but there is a great
deal of support for it.

00:39:28.150 --> 00:39:32.170
That it was the growing
complexity of social interactions,

00:39:32.170 --> 00:39:38.210
whether in raising offspring,
in interacting with each other.

00:39:38.210 --> 00:39:42.910
That may have been the driving
force in driving brain growth.

00:39:42.910 --> 00:39:47.180 position:56%
So, in my opinion, this is the best.

00:39:47.180 --> 00:39:52.150
And it's inextricably bound up
with the idea of social selection.

00:39:52.150 --> 00:39:56.430
Namely, the idea that social
interactions strengthen

00:39:56.430 --> 00:39:57.920
social cohesion.

00:39:57.920 --> 00:40:00.160
Which promotes the survival
of the group, and thereby,

00:40:00.160 --> 00:40:01.910
of its individual members.

00:40:01.910 --> 00:40:05.430
And here I've allowed myself
to give one reference.

00:40:05.430 --> 00:40:09.110
This idea has, I think, not
really been given enough play.

00:40:09.110 --> 00:40:13.350
But this idea was first explained
by a guy named Herbert Simon,

00:40:13.350 --> 00:40:15.190
who is an economist,
not a biologist.

00:40:15.190 --> 00:40:17.790
But somebody with a
very great range.

00:40:17.790 --> 00:40:24.160
And the idea simply is that we are
necessarily a cooperative species.

00:40:24.160 --> 00:40:26.130
Certainly, in our early
days, we needed a lot

00:40:26.130 --> 00:40:28.130
of cooperation to get things done.

00:40:28.130 --> 00:40:33.720
You take the human and put him
or her out on his or her own,

00:40:33.720 --> 00:40:37.310
and that person's survival
will be rapidly compromised.

00:40:37.310 --> 00:40:39.920
We are inherently a social animal

00:40:39.920 --> 00:40:45.430
and we need our social
cohesion, in order to survive.

00:40:45.430 --> 00:40:49.200
I realize that I'm not giving
this argument in its full details

00:40:49.200 --> 00:40:51.230
and merits, but that's
just because of time.

00:40:51.230 --> 00:40:53.740
But I would recommend if anybody's
interested in following it up,

00:40:53.740 --> 00:40:57.400
looking at this article
by Herbert Simon.

00:40:57.400 --> 00:41:00.550
Now, three key points to
that social selection.

00:41:00.550 --> 00:41:02.900
It's not the same as
group selection.

00:41:02.900 --> 00:41:06.790
Group selection posits that certain
things evolved because they were

00:41:06.790 --> 00:41:08.410
for the good of the group.

00:41:08.410 --> 00:41:11.470
Instead, the idea of
social selection posits

00:41:11.470 --> 00:41:14.980
that there was strength in social
bonds that were a direct benefit

00:41:14.980 --> 00:41:18.810
to the individual,
often at minimal cost.

00:41:18.810 --> 00:41:21.910
Okay. Again, that deserves
more explanation

00:41:21.910 --> 00:41:23.210
than I can give it, here.

00:41:23.210 --> 00:41:24.740
But that is a key idea.

00:41:24.740 --> 00:41:27.600
For humans, the evolution of
social interactions must have been,

00:41:27.600 --> 00:41:30.460
to some degree, coupled with
the evolution of language.

00:41:30.460 --> 00:41:34.840
Okay. It's hard to convey your wish

00:41:34.840 --> 00:41:38.190
to do things cooperatively
without language.

00:41:38.190 --> 00:41:40.460
You can do it to some
extent, and animals do.

00:41:40.460 --> 00:41:45.110
But language had almost undoubtedly
been of crucial importance

00:41:45.110 --> 00:41:48.050
in our evolution as a species.

00:41:48.050 --> 00:41:50.530
Finally, the evolution of
language was almost certainly tied

00:41:50.530 --> 00:41:52.080
up with both the evolution
of the brain

00:41:52.080 --> 00:41:55.450
and of facial expressions
accompanying speech.

00:41:56.520 --> 00:42:03.740
But faces, in that last point,
